[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   We have \(n\) students and \(k\) independent “same‐group” relations (one per course), each relation defining connected components via transitivity.  Two students are “good buddies” if they lie in the same component in **every** course.  We must count, for each student, how many students share **all** \(k\) components with them.  
   This is essentially a DSU (union–find) problem to build per‐course components, followed by grouping identical \(k\)-tuples (one tuple per student).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   - For each of the \(k\) courses, run a DSU on the \(n\) students using the given pairwise relations to find component roots.  
   - For each student, record a length-\(k\) tuple of their root IDs (one root per course).  
   - Sort the students by these tuples.  Consecutive students in the sorted order with identical tuples form a group of mutual good-buddies; the group size is their answer.  

   Sorting these \(n\) tuples (each of size \(k\)) lets us in one pass assign each student the size of their identical‐tuple block.

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - DSU building: \(\sum_i (m_i\alpha(n)) + nk\alpha(n)\), with \(\sum m_i\le5\times10^5\) and \(nk\le5\times10^5\).  
   - Sorting \(n\) vectors of length \(k\): \(O(n\log n\cdot k)\).  
   Overall well within typical contest limits.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - A course may have zero relations; every student is in a singleton group.  
   - All students may end up in one group for some courses.  
   - Distinct DSU instances must be reset per course.  
   - Make sure to restore original student ordering for output.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Problem: Count for each student how many others share the same
   DSU component in ALL k courses.  
   Techniques: k×DSU to get per-course roots, then sort students
   by their k-dimensional “root signature” and count identical blocks.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

// Simple Union-Find (DSU) with path compression & union by rank
struct DSU {
    vector<int> p, r;
    DSU(int n): p(n), r(n,0) {
        iota(p.begin(), p.end(), 0);
    }
    int find(int x) {
        return p[x] == x ? x : (p[x] = find(p[x]));
    }
    void unite(int a, int b) {
        a = find(a); b = find(b);
        if (a == b) return;
        if (r[a] < r[b]) swap(a, b);
        p[b] = a;
        if (r[a] == r[b]) r[a]++;
    }
};

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, k;
    cin >> n >> k;
    // comp[i][j] = root of student i in course j
    vector<vector<int>> comp(n, vector<int>(k));

    for (int course = 0; course < k; course++) {
        int m; 
        cin >> m;
        DSU dsu(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            int u, v;
            cin >> u >> v;
            --u; --v;
            dsu.unite(u, v);
        }
        // Record each student's root for this course
        for (int student = 0; student < n; student++) {
            comp[student][course] = dsu.find(student);
        }
    }

    // Prepare indices [0..n-1] to sort by their comp-vectors
    vector<int> idx(n);
    iota(idx.begin(), idx.end(), 0);
    sort(idx.begin(), idx.end(), [&](int a, int b){
        return comp[a] < comp[b];
    });

    // ans[i] = number of students sharing the same k-tuple with i
    vector<int> ans(n);
    int start = 0;
    // Traverse sorted indices grouping equal comp-vectors
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        if (i == n || comp[idx[i]] != comp[idx[i-1]]) {
            int groupSize = i - start;
            for (int j = start; j < i; j++) {
                ans[idx[j]] = groupSize;
            }
            start = i;
        }
    }

    // Output
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << ans[i] << (i+1<n ? ' ' : '\n');
    }
    return 0;
}
